By the time he arrived, there were four indigenous tribes in Costa Rica&ndash; the Caribs, Borucas, Chibchas, and Diqu&iacute;s tribes.</p>\n<p>Few of these indigenous peoples survived the dawn of Spanish colonialism, and African slaves were brought in to work the land.</p>\n<p>Despite its colonial past, Costa Rica eventually managed to achieve a lasting democracy. ARENAL VOLCANO NATIONAL PARK</h2>\n<p>One of the most active volcanoes in the world until 2010, the 5,480-foot Arenal Volcano dominates the landscape of northwestern Costa Rica. Located near the tiny town of La Fortuna, the volcano has been dormant for years. But the area remains a popular ecotourism destination thanks to Lake Arenal, La Fortuna Waterfall, and various hot springs. BALLENA MARINE NATIONAL PARK</h2>\n<p>Ballena Marine National Park, one of the newest national parks in Costa Rica, is widely considered among the best places in the Americas for whale-watching. The park also offers 8.69 miles of beautiful beaches, a small estuary, and snorkeling Central America&rsquo;s largest coral reef on the Pacific Ocean.</p>\n<h3>3. CA&Ntilde;O ISLAND</h3>\n<p>Located off the coast of the Osa Peninsula, Ca&ntilde;o Island became a biological reserve in 1978. Among the island&rsquo;s towering evergreens, the Diqu&iacute;s tribe&rsquo;s hand-carved stone spheres have baffled archeologists for years. Ca&ntilde;o Island is considered one of the world&rsquo;s best Scuba diving spots: It&rsquo;s surrounded by five platforms of coral reefs. Divers have the chance to see Eels, Lobsters, Sharks, Sea Turtles, and possibly Whales during winter.</p>\n<h2>4.&nbsp;CORCOVADO NATIONAL PARK</h2>\n<p>Described by National Geographic as &ldquo;the most biologically intense place on earth,&rdquo; Corcovado National Park is the largest in Costa Rica. There are 13 different ecosystems here, with extensive trails through highland cloud forest, mangrove swamps, lowland rain forests, and sandy beaches. MANUEL ANTONIO NATIONAL PARK</h2>\n<p>Ranked among the world&rsquo;s most beautiful national parks by Forbes, Manuel Antonio annually attracts around 150,000 visitors. They&rsquo;re drawn by its beautiful beaches and hiking trails through primary forest, secondary forest, mangrove swamps, and lagoons. The park boasts 184 species of birds and 109 species of mammals.
